  "response_text": "The mean household initial risk attitude remains constant across all time steps, hovering consistently at approximately 0.065. This unchanging value suggests that, under homogeneous behavioral conditions (all E-RO agents with homogenized behavioral types), risk attitudes exhibit no temporal variation. The absence of fluctuation aligns with the absence of learning mechanisms (social learning disabled via homog-behav-types?, satisfaction-based strategies inactive) and the static parameterization of risk-att-init (0.5 global value). The model's focus on E-RO agents in a homogeneous setup inherently limits adaptive behavioral shifts, resulting in a baseline risk attitude profile that persists unchanged throughout the 100-step simulation. This static trend underscores the model's control over behavioral homogeneity in evaluating baseline risk disposition prior to introducing heterogeneity or learning extensions."  
  }

